- If `i < j`, it returns `¤ë (Ôş¿(i, j), le_of_lt h_ltÔş®)`, which is the (i,j) off-diagonal entry according to the measure `╬╝`.
- If `j < i`, it returns `¤ë (Ôş¿(j, i), le_of_lt h_gtÔş®)`, which is the (j,i) off-diagonal entry. Due to symmetry, this should be equal to the (i,j) entry.

So, the function `fun ¤ë ÔåĞ (wignerMatrixMap n ¤ë) i j` is equal to `fun ¤ë ÔåĞ wignerMatrixEntryFunction ¤ë i j`. Since we're assuming `i < j`, this means the function is `fun ¤ë ÔåĞ ¤ë (Ôş¿(i, j), le_of_lt h_ltÔş®)`, which is precisely the function that represents the off-diagonal entry in the sample space `WignerSpace n`.

