- Diagonal entries `M i i` are `¤ë Ôş¿(i, i), le_refl iÔş®` (which has law `╬¢`).
- Upper off-diagonal entries `M i j` for `i < j` are `¤ë Ôş¿(i, j), by simp [i, j, Finset.mem_range]; tautoÔş®` (which has law `╬╝`).
- Lower off-diagonal entries `M j i` for `j < i` are `¤ë Ôş¿(j, i), by simp [j, i, Finset.mem_range]; tautoÔş®` (which also has law `╬╝` due to symmetry).

The proof requires showing `HasLaw (fun ¤ë ÔåĞ (wignerMatrixMap n ¤ë) i j) ╬╝ (WignerMeasure ╬╝ ╬¢ n)`. This means we need to show that the random variable `X = fun ¤ë ÔåĞ (wignerMatrixMap n ¤ë) i j` has the law `╬╝` under the probability measure `WignerMeasure ╬╝ ╬¢ n`.

The key insight is that `wignerMatrixMap n` is a measurable function from `WignerSpace n` to `Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ÔäØ`, and `WignerMeasure ╬╝ ╬¢ n` is a probability measure on `WignerSpace n`. The measure `WignerMeasure ╬╝ ╬¢ n` is constructed as the product measure of `╬╝` and `╬¢` on the coordinates of the matrix.

For the entry `(i, j)` where `i < j`:
- The value of the matrix entry `M i j` is determined by the value of the function `¤ë` at the point `Ôş¿(i, j), by simp [i, j, Finset.mem_range]; tautoÔş®` in `WignerSpace n`.
- Since `WignerMeasure ╬╝ ╬¢ n` is the product measure, the coordinates are independent.
- Specifically, for the upper off-diagonal entries, the coordinates are assigned the measure `╬╝`.

