First, we need to understand what the Wigner Matrix is. The problem defines it as a matrix where the diagonal entries have law `╬¢` and the off-diagonal entries have law `╬╝`. The matrix is symmetric, meaning that the entry at `(i, j)` is the same as the entry at `(j, i)`.

To prove that the entry at `(i, j)` (where `i < j`) has law `╬╝`, we need to show that this entry is identically distributed to some random variable with law `╬╝`. 

